node.text:
One of my patients sent me this video from @jillianmichaels about the new drug semaglutide. She has a gross misunderstanding of obesity and why people fail to lose weight along with how these trials are run.

I forgot to add in a quick segment about the fear of thyroid cancer. It is a very rare type of thyroid cancer that rats are predisposed to. There is no signal that this occurs in humans.

I have many patients on this medicine who finally feel they have a normal appetite. It’s not that they lack willpower, it’s because it’s physiology! Let me know what you think of the video.

node.text: I tried to distill my usual hour long lectures on weight loss and hormones into 5 minutes. Basically it still comes down to calories BUT hormones are intertwined to where we cannot separate them completely. ❤️

node.text: People love to take things to the extreme. Don’t drink sugar or butter 😂

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dr. Spencer Nadolsky on September 04, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'UNLESS YOU STOLEIT, EATING-ANY FOOD SHOULD FEEL GUILT FREE'.

node.text:
I’d say most people have felt guilt from eating something at one point in their life. Some people may even feel it on a daily basis. Remember that it’s all just energy. Some of these foods are more readily overeaten than others and contain fewer nutrients… but you shouldn’t feel guilt from eating them.

Yes, ideally we would eat mostly whole unprocessed nutrient dense foods. But let go of the guilt you get when eating the other foods. In doing so, you’ll be able to focus on improvement. ❤️❤️

Ps I agree with those who have mentioned it’s okay if you’re starving and you have to get what you can to survive ❤️❤️

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dr. Spencer Nadolsky on September 03, 2021. May be a meme of text that says '"Regular soda is better for you than diet soda." Me: Caps Lock @DrNadolsky'.

node.text:
I got tagged a bunch of times a week or so ago on some guru’s page who was saying regular soda is better for you than diet soda. My god I can’t believe people listen to these idiots.

Anyway, if you want to see an academic discussion about this, my brother @drkarlnadolsky wrote a review for Endocrine Practice. I put the link in my stories. Just swipe up when you see this meme.

node.text:
I don’t generally recommend whole grains unless I’m very specific where to get them. Of course the fish part is obvious but some may see these and say hey they are whole grains!

Ridiculous. If eating whole grains, go to the least processed version. Like whole or steel cut oats.

❤️❤️❤️

May be an image of 3 people and text that says '"Calories don't matter." @DrNadolsky "Cholesterol and saturated fat are good for you." "I can fix your adrenals and thyroid without medicine." "Doctors are paid off by big pharma." "I am an online health and fitness guru."'.

node.text:
This seems to be common amongst the online fitness gurus. These statements are CLASSIC!!

1. Calories do absolutely matter when it comes to losing weight. Of course other things matter on top of that, but you’ll see people try to say things like as long as your insulin is low, calories don’t matter or something like that. It’s nonsense!

2. You don’t need to eat cholesterol. Our cells make plenty. Also an interesting tidbit, most of the cholesterol in our intestines is actually not from our diet anyway. Most of it is from bile. You also don’t need to eat saturated fat. It’s not required for proper health. You don’t need it for hormone production.

3. Everyone wants to be an endocrinologist but no one wants to go through medical school then residency then fellowship. These gurus start pushing some nonsense protocols to fix your adrenal glands and thyroid. If you see this, just unfollow.

4. We have to go based on the data out there regarding drugs. Doctors don’t get paid based on how many drugs they prescribe from various big pharma companies. That’s a myth! Doctors do get paid to speak about certain drugs and help with research. I’m A OKAY with this. In fact I may do this.

Anyway just a funny cluster of sayings to look out for. ❤️❤️❤️❤️

node.text:
I know I’m a broken record but it bears repeating. There is no special macronutrient ratio that is best for fat loss. Sure, we recommend having sufficient protein to minimize muscle loss when losing weight, but even then there is a lot of wiggle room there.

You don’t need to go keto. Or low fat.

You need to find the best way to eat for YOU to be in a calorie deficit. This usually means satiating foods that are lower in energy (calories). But you can still enjoy higher calorie yummy foods too if it doesn’t send you into a hedonic food fest (think eating one chip then eating the rest of the bag).

If you want to go low carb you certainly can too! I won’t stop you 😂❤️

This is type 2 diabetes btw. Some people were upset that it’s possible our bodies compensate to lessen the effects of exercise on weight loss. Don’t be upset. We’ve known that exercise by itself isn’t great for weight loss.

You should still do it if possible though because it does help.

But first, focus on your nutrition. I’ve had many patients like this lose 10-50% of their weight and keep most of it off and resolve weight related issues by following the principles we know help.

Don’t focus on mostly meaningless numbers like metabolic rate. Look at outcomes of health and body composition. Exercise (especially a combo of resistance and aerobic training) help with that regardless of the number on the scale. Add it with nutrition and you have a formula for success.

If appetite is an issue despite best practices, again, we have medicines and surgery if needed. ❤️❤️

node.text:
Had to make another GOAT Spider-Man meme related to this morning’s study post.

To make this simple to understand, weight loss comes down to energy balance. That means eating fewer calories than you burn.

So either eat fewer calories or move more to burn more calories or both right? Sure! But as you add more physical activity, there becomes a point where our TOTAL calorie burn for the day (total daily energy expenditure) doesn’t increase in an additive fashion.

For example, let’s say you burn 2000 calories per day just living (Basal metabolic rate). Now you add what you believe to be 1000 calories of physical activity. Either from walking or chores plus some form of purposeful exercise like running or biking. We think we should be burning a total of 3000 calories per day from just living and physical activity (not including the thermic effect of food). But what actually happens is less than an additive amount of calories burned. It seems as though through whatever mechanisms we burn fewer than we think. In this case maybe we would only be burning 2500 calories (hard to know for sure with the individual).

Take home point: focus more so on diet for weight loss. Exercise is great for you and can help slightly with weight loss (especially maintenance of weight loss). Exercise won’t help as much as people think for weight loss. Make sure you lift weights to keep the muscle as you lose fat. Don’t do it necessarily for the calorie burn. ❤️❤️

node.text:
A new study shows that we probably don’t burn as many calories in total per day that we think when adding in physical activity.

This does NOT mean that exercise is worthless for weight loss. It is just not nearly as important as diet when it comes to weight loss. This may be even more important for those with extra body fat (see pic).

I speculate as well that there are differences long term when looking at types of physical activity. Weight lifting should be included in your program if possible!

This has the same authors as the study I posted a couple weeks ago. Interesting stuff. Lucky enough to be in close contract to them for this type of breaking research. ❤️
